Kubernetes Cluster Components and Communication

Two Main Parts
Control Plane = The Boss and managers. Controls everything.
Worker Nodes = The employees. Actually run the containers and pods.

# Control Plane Components

1. Kube-API Server - The Boss

This is the central communication hub. Every component talks to API Server.

Who talks to API Server:

kubectl (you, the admin)
kube-scheduler
kube-controller-manager
etcd (database)
Worker nodes (kubelet)

Real benefit: One single entry point for all management. Easy to secure and monitor.

2. etcd - The Database

Stores all cluster data like running pods, nodes, and configurations.
Only API Server can talk to etcd directly.

Real benefit: Single source of truth. If etcd is safe, your whole cluster state is safe.

3. Kube-Scheduler - The Planner

Decides which worker node should run a new pod.
Talks only to API Server, not directly to worker nodes.

Real benefit: Automatic and smart placement of workloads. You don't need to manually assign nodes.

4. Kube-Controller-Manager - The Manager

Runs controllers that monitor the cluster and fix issues automatically.
Talks only to API Server.

Real benefit: Self healing. If a pod dies, controller manager creates a new one without asking you.

5. Cloud-Controller-Manager - The Cloud Boss

Only used in cloud environments like AWS, GCP, Azure.
Manages cloud resources like load balancers and storage.
Talks to API Server and cloud provider APIs.

Real benefit: Kubernetes can automatically create cloud resources when needed.

# Worker Node Components

1. Kubelet - The Worker Boss

Runs on every worker node.
Talks to API Server to get pod assignments.
Talks to container runtime to start and stop containers.

Real benefit: Keeps API Server updated about node health. If node is down, control plane knows immediately.

2. Container Runtime

Actually runs the containers inside pods.
Examples: Docker, containerd, CRI-O.
Only talks to kubelet.

Real benefit: Multiple runtime options. You are not locked into one technology.

3. Kube Proxy - The Network Controller

Manages network rules so pods can talk to each other.
Talks to API Server to get network rules.

Real benefit: Pods can communicate across different worker nodes without complex network setup.

Complete Communication Flow
When you create a pod using kubectl apply:

Step	Action
1	    kubectl sends request to API Server
2	    API Server stores the request in etcd
3	    Scheduler checks for unscheduled pods
4	    Scheduler assigns pod to a worker node
5	    Scheduler updates API Server with the decision
6	    API Server tells kubelet on that worker node
7	    Kubelet asks container runtime to start the container
8	    Container runtime starts the pod
9	    Kubelet reports status back to API Server
10	    Kube Proxy sets up networking if needed


Final Simple Rule
Everything goes through the API Server. It is the center of all communication.

Worker nodes do not talk directly to control plane components. They only talk to API Server.

Real benefit for IT working: This design makes Kubernetes secure, easy to debug, and scalable. You can upgrade any component without breaking others because communication is centralized.


